observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to strictly observe Section 43, Chapter 3, Volume I of the Manual on the New Government Accounting System (MNGAS) for LGUs in the preparation of RCI and in the reporting of checks issued;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to strictly observe Section 42, Chapter 3, Volume I of the Manual on the New Government Accounting System (MNGAS) for LGUs in the preparation of Check Register and in the reporting of released checks;
Require the Municipal Accountant to immediately submit the lacking Disbursement Vouchers and its supporting documents, otherwise the transactions covered by the unsubmitted documents amounting to ₱10,128,457.79 shall be suspended in audit; and
Require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to submit written justification why they did not secure the approval of the LCE thru a duly signed Disbursement Voucher before payment was made from the online account of the local government unit.

We recommended to Management the following:
Require the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of inventory items as of June 30 and December 31 of each year. It shall prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) by inventory account name and distribute it as prescribed. Furthermore, the Inventory Committee shall reconcile the RPCI with the records of the Municipal Accounting Office in accordance with Section 124, Chapter 4 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume I. A duplicate copy of the RPCI shall be submitted to the Office of the Auditor no later than July 31 and January 31 for the first and second semesters, respectively;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to adopt the moving average method as the costing method for inventory valuation as prescribed under Section 115, Chapter 7 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume I;
Instruct the Municipal General Services Officer (GSO) and the Municipal Accountant to maintain updated Stock Cards and Supplies Ledger Cards, respectively, for all types of inventories and conduct regular reconciliation to detect discrepancies and implement immediate corrections; and
Direct the Municipal GSO to promptly prepare and submit the weekly Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) to the Municipal Accountant for proper recording in compliance with Sections 119 and 120, Chapter 7 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I;

We recommended to Management the following:
Direct the Inventory Committee to prepare and submit the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System of the local government unit;
Direct the Municipal General Services Officer to prepare the Report on Local Road Network, maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map, and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components;
Direct the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal General Services Officer with a complete description and cost segregation of road components for all road projects; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements, prepare the Local Road Network Ledger Card, and ensure the timely recording of completed road projects and recompute the depreciation for Calendar Year 2024 to reflect the accurate asset valuation and reliable financial reporting.

We reiterated our recommendations from the previous year that Management:
Return the unexpended balances amounting to ₱163,472.29 to the various barangays to fully settle the obligations;
Comply with Section 33 of R.A. No. 7160 by executing Memoranda of Agreement with the concerned barangays regarding the implementation of counterpart projects aggregating to ₱3,377,906.31;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the fund transfers are recorded in both the books of the LGU and the barangays to establish accountability and responsibility, in line with COA Circular No. 94-013 dated December 13, 1994;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare and submit the necessary supporting schedules, such as the aging report and Subsidiary Ledgers for each creditor, to facilitate the monitoring and evaluation of accounts; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to reclassify the LGU counterpart funds as Trust Liabilities in accordance with Annex B of COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015, also known as the Revised Chart of Accounts (RCA) for Local Government Units.

We recommended to Management the following:
Establish clear-cut guidelines on selecting qualified small local farmers or Farmers’ Cooperatives/Associations as beneficiaries of the fifty (50) percent of the goat produce pursuant to the Memorandum of Agreement with the Department of Agriculture;
The Sangguniang Bayan to enact an ordinance to regulate the sale of the remaining fifty (50) percent of the goat produce, in accordance with the Memorandum of Agreement with the Department of Agriculture and in line with Section 305(c) of Republic Act No. 7160; and
The Municipal Mayor to install and implement adequate internal control measures in the management of the San Mateo Goat Multiplier Breeder Project to ensure its sustainability and to prevent further loss of the goats or wastage of government funds, in line with Sections 123 and 124 of P.D. No. 1445;

We recommended to Management the following:
Require the Municipal GSO to prepare and maintain the required Stock Cards and Inventory List of Items for DRRM to properly document and monitor the receipt, transfer and issuance of procured welfare goods;
Require the Municipal Budget Officer to submit a written explanation on the charging of procured welfare goods against different Programs, Projects, and Activities (PPAs) without first securing a revised Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund Investment Plan (LDRRMFIP);
Require the Municipal Budget Officer to submit a written justification on the use of the 30% Quick Response Fund (QRF) without securing first the approved declaration of State of Calamity;
Direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal General Services Officer to submit a written explanation on the lacking documentation on the distribution of welfare goods; and
Direct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to submit a written explanation for recommending to the Head of Procuring Entity (HoPE) the adoption of Negotiated Procurement - Emergency Cases in the procurement of welfare goods prior to securing the approval of the declaration of State of Calamity.

We recommended to Management the following:
Designate a Petty Cash Fund Custodian in the Municipal Treasury Office, except the Municipal Treasurer, to enforce proper segregation of duties, ensure checks and balances, and avoid transfer of cash advances from one accountable officer to another;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to submit his Authority as the Accountable Officer issued by the Head of the Agency or his/her authorized representative indicating the maximum accountability and the specific purpose of cash advance (Petty Cash Fund) in compliance with COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012;
Require the Municipal Treasurer and the Disbursing Officer to ensure that payments through checks and cash shall be made directly to the creditor/payee to whom the money is due in compliance with existing COA rules and regulations; and
Install, implement and monitor sound system of internal control in all the transactions and operations of the LGU in line with Sections 123 and 124of P.D. No. 1445.

We recommended that Management:

Record in the books the parcel of land omitted in the Financial Statements;



Process the transfer of the land ownership through the Torrens System;



Provide the copies of the Deed of Sale or other instruments evidencing the legal claim of the LGU over the various parcels of land;

Require the General Services Officer as property custodian to locate all the missing owner’s duplicate copies of the Land Titles as listed in Annex I;

Provide copies of the Capital Gains Tax Returns paid by the various sellers of land;



Provide the Electronic Copies of all the Land Titles listed in Annex I;





Provide justification for the failure of transferring the land ownership into the name of the LGU;

Require the Municipal Assessor to provide justification regarding his custody of the Owner’s Duplicate Copy of the TCT not being one of his mandated duties and functions;

Provide Status on the registration of the acquired parcel of lot in the name of the Local Government Unit of San Mateo; and

Submit an updated report on the PPE One-Time Cleansing of the Municipality.

We recommended to Management the following:
Ensure that the appropriated amounts of the 20% Development Fund are fully utilized in the implementation of the lined-up projects contained in the approved Annual Investment Plan (AIP);
Instruct the Municipal Planning and Development Council (MPDC) to include in the Annual Investment Plan (AIP) only those projects that can be implemented during the year through efficient planning and procurement activities in line with Section 3.2.3 of DBM-DOF-DILG Joint Memorandum Circular (JMC) No. 1 dated November 4, 2020;
Direct the Municipal Engineer, in cooperation with the Municipal Budget Officer and the Municipal Accountant, to closely monitor the utilization of funds and implementation of priority projects which are essential to the promotion of general welfare of the people and to maximize the usage of the 20% development fund as mandated under DILG-DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2017-1; and
If necessary, consider requesting for the reprogramming of the savings from the completed projects totaling to ₱1,736,622.53 to other development projects which will be contained in the revised Annual Investment Plan (AIP) to facilitate its appropriate release and utilization.

We recommended that the Municipal Treasurer to:
Direct the concerned personnel in the Municipal Treasury Office to prepare the RCI using the prescribed format and instructions in Form No. 47 of NGAS Manual for LGU, Volume II and submit the RCI to the Office of the Auditor as stated in Section 43 of the New Government Accounting System (NGAS) Manual for LGU, Volume I;
Instruct the preparer of checks in the Municipal Treasury Office to be cautious in entering data in the face of the checks and devise a control measure to avoid frequent error in the preparation of checks;

The Municipal Accountant must reconcile the above-noted variance in the 20% Development Fund appearing in the Notes to FS, and SCBAA and FUR, and thereafter, undertake the same regularly; 

Submit specific details of the Outstanding Checks in the General Fund Proper as at December 31, 2022 totaling ₱12,096,938.15; and

Cash accounts must be monitored consistently and should be presented fairly in accordance with IPSAS 1 and other accounting rules and regulations.

Device concrete plans and strategies that shall be effective in monitoring the existence and availability of cash before incurrence of expenditures;

Consider adopting austerity measures on expenditures vis-à-vis available cash and other fiscal resources; and

Ensure that the balances of appropriation/allotment coincide with and be properly supported by certified available cash before committing/obligating and disbursing funds.

The Municipal Mayor shall ensure submission of Memorandum of Agreement and supporting documents to the Office of the Auditor within five (5) working days from perfection thereof, in keeping with COA Circular No. 2009-001; 

Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer and implementing departments shall coordinate and confirm whether projects charged to the above-mentioned fund transfers were actually completed and determine whether there are any other outstanding obligations chargeable to the funds;

Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer shall determine if the unutilized balances accrue to the National Government Agencies and Government-Owned Corporations or the LGU in instances of counterpart funds;

For funds accruing the NGAs and GOCCs, immediately return the unexpended balances as at year-end to these Source Agencies (SA). If the SA cannot be identified, immediately remit the remaining idle funds to the Bureau of Treasury; and

For counterpart LGU funds, the Local Finance Committee shall undertake corresponding evaluation and give recommendation on the proper disposition of funds to other priority projects.

Management must (1) present for inspection the remaining four (4) heads of originally procured goats with aggregate cost of ₱140,000.00 which were not presented during ocular inspection and (2) submit documents to support dispersal of swine and cattle and donation of red tilapias for evaluation in audit;


The Municipal Accountant shall record the necessary adjustments for the costs of births, distributions/dispersals, deaths and changes in fair market values due to price and physical changes and thereafter, prudently comply to the specific guidelines of IPSAS 27 and other relevant issuances;

The Municipal Agriculturist shall regularly submit Inventory Report of Breeding Stocks with information on births, distributions/transfers, deaths and fair market values and furnish the same to the Office of the Municipal Account for proper accounting and reconciliation; and

The Municipal Accountant and Municipal Agriculturist shall regularly reconcile their records to promptly address variances that may arise.

The Municipal Mayor compel the concerned employees and officials to pay back in full the amounts shouldered by the LGU for their salary loan amortizations and be reverted back to the funds on which payments were taken;

Only the amounts deducted for salary loan amortizations shall be remitted by the Municipal Treasury Office to the lending institutions, and any late payment of obligations as well as corresponding interest and penalties shall be personally borne by the defaulting employees and officials;

The Municipal Mayor stop the practice of over-the-counter payment and require instead the employees and officials to directly pay outstanding loan obligations to the lending institutions;

Management review the terms and conditions of the Memoranda of Agreement entered by the LGU as collecting agency and the Lending Institutions, and initiate revisions that will accommodate the immediately preceding two (2) recommendations, in favor of the LGU;

The Municipal Mayor along with other concerned employees should be vigilant in the granting of additional loans and should give emphasis on the prevention of additional loans which may contravene the GAA provision requiring ₱5,000.00 minimum net take home pay;

All employees and officials should update their loan amortizations to make sure that all payments deducted from their salaries have been duly remitted and pay back all payments improperly shouldered by the LGU on their behalf; and

The Municipal Mayor to assign the preparation of payroll deductions and remittances to the Accounting Office and Treasury Office, respectively, for proper check and balance, as such duties should not be handled by one and the same person.

We also recommended the Accounting Office to conduct regular reconciliation of salary loan amortization deductions and remittances.

We recommended management the following:

Submit Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption for every government motor transportation, supported with duly approved RIS, duly filled-up trip tickets and charge invoices;

Enforce the rule of prohibiting private vehicles to be issued with fuel out of government funds as mandated under Item 3.1.1.8 of COA Circular No. 96-004 or stop the practice of allowing private vehicles to claim fuel, oil and lubricant out of government resources;

Strictly prohibit erasures in the gas slips, trip tickets and charge invoices and sanctions may be imposed, if appropriate and could warrant the issuance of Notices of Suspension or Disallowance; and

Require the refund of unnecessary claims of fuel by these private vehicles to prevent audit disallowance.

We recommended Management the following:
Instruct the General Services Officer to timely and completely submit the Report on Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment;
Require the General Services Officer to submit the Inventory and Inspection Report for Unserviceable Property to facilitate the disposal of unserviceable properties and instruct the Disposal Committee to expedite the disposal of unserviceable properties following the procedures set forth in COA Circular No. 92-386 to prevent further deterioration and to realize income therefrom, if found to be saleable;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjusting entries on the misclassified account;
Fully effect the mark “FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY” observing the required size of three (3) inches and the corresponding name of the LGU on each side of the vehicle to prevent unnecessary and unofficial use of government vehicles;
Ensure that all properties of the LGU are registered in the name of the Municipality of San Mateo and bear government plates;
Strictly comply with the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability; and
Fairly present in the financial statements the substance of transactions, not merely their form, to achieve a more faithfully represented PPE account in compliance to IPSAS 1.

We recommended Management to:
Stop the utilization of cash from other bank accounts for disbursements pertaining to 5% LDRRM Fund and 20% Development Fund since these have their separate specific bank accounts;
Instruct both the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to reconcile both their records and make the corresponding adjustments to whichever record has the error. Likewise, the former must (1) reconcile and adjust the TL-DRRMF and Cash in Bank-LDRRMF and (2) transfer the correct CIB-LDRRMF in the Trust Fund books and the Municipal Treasurer must transfer corresponding cash to its separate bank account;
Require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Budget Officer to reconcile their records to correctly establish the balances for the 20% Development Fund and with the corrected balance, the Municipal Treasurer shall determine cash for transfer to its separate bank account;
Order the Municipal Treasurer to prepare and submit the Report of Checks Issued per bank account and fund in accordance with the prescribed format in Annex 47 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs and disclose on the report all cancelled or voided or unclaimed checks for easy monitoring and validation; and
Consistently monitor the Cash accounts and that it should be presented fairly in accordance with IPSAS 1 and other accounting rules and regulations.

We recommended Management to:
Require the Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjusting entries to correct the balances of the “Accounts Payable” and “Trust Liabilities” accounts and to properly recognize receipts from sale of bid documents in accordance with COA Circular No. 2015-009;
Withhold taxes on payments of BAC honoraria and ensure remittance to BIR within the prescribed period;
Submit justification and legal basis for granting honoraria to observers, otherwise it will be subjected to refund and any future payments must be stopped; and
Ensure that payments of BAC honoraria are duly supported with complete documentation.

We recommended that the following required documents be submitted to support the completeness, validity and authenticity of the payment.

Authority for the entitlement to these allowances;

Terms of Reference/Memorandum of Undertaking with provisions for authority to pay private health workers, if there’s any;

Certificate of Attendance during the ECQ/MECQ period; 

Inter-Agency Task Force for Management of Infectious Disease (IATF) Resolution of the Risk Classification in the workplace;

Period and the number of days these recipients physically reported for work during ECQ in support to the liquidation of Ᵽ5,131,363.29 granted by DOH; and

Provide justifiable reason in granting both hazard pay from the general fund and Department of Health (DOH).

We recommended that Management:

a. Submit a justification/explanation on the above observations;

b. Thru its Bids and Awards Committee (BAC), ensure strict conformity with the provisions of R.A. 9184 and its RIRR in all of its procurement, the conduct of a careful evaluation of bid documents, its bidders so that more qualified and eligible contractors/suppliers can participate and enable the government to obtain the most advantageous contracts and to preclude any issues that may arise from the implementation of the projects.

We recommended that the management in coordination with the Sangguniang Bayan to:

a. enforce collection of overdue receivables from water system, Pasalubong Center, Munggo Processing and Packaging Center as well as stall rentals and leasehold right occupancy fees;

b. provide with Lease Contract Agreement all qualified lessee;

c. strictly impose the pertinent provisions of Market Code, Local Ordinance No. 2011-606 to all delinquent tenants; and

d. send demand letters to all concerned compelling them to immediately settle their balances.

We recommended that Management:

a. Require all Collecting Officers to maintain CRR, and shall reconcile the cash balances with the accounting records on a monthly basis;

b. Require the Accounting Office to have its own recording and monitoring tool for the Pay CR, for the proper accounting and monitoring of the income derived therefrom;

c. Require the Collecting Officers to be permanent employees bonded with the Bureau of Treasury; and

d. Ensure that the collection function be handled primarily by the MTO.

We recommended management to closely monitor and strengthen controls on the operations of the pay comfort rooms where the risks existed to ensure that funds collected therefrom will be remitted to the coffers of the LGU. Hence, the Audit Team further recommended that management consider the following:

a. Issue cash tickets to all the users of the pay CR;

b. Regular employees be assigned to collect CR fees;

c. Analyze collection trends by capturing on a daily/monthly basis to determine the standard actual collections; and 

d. Proper supervision be made to ensure that all cash collected are reported and remitted to the coffers of the municipal government.

